<p>Made from old enamel, the jug is typical of Karoo households at the time. Martins had a small toiletry station in the far corner of the Long Bedroom.</p>
<p>&ldquo;As Helen's house had no running water, no connection to a water mains, all water had to be collected in buckets from the sluice up the road and water for washing would have been decanted into this sort of jug. Water (and hence water containers, are another important symbol at the Owl House. Water washes off the dust and dirt of the day and is about renewal and refreshment. It also permits the life of nature, enables the creation of a paradise garden (and Helen, in part, was creating her version of paradise at the Owl House&rdquo; (Graaff, personal communication 2017, 27 October).</p>